                <h class="subheading1" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="100"><br>Understanding Added Sugars</h>

                <p>
                    <br />
                    Added (Free) sugars are sweeteners that are added to foods and drinks to enhance flavour. As written by <a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/does-sugar-make-you-fat">Kubala (2019)</a>, excess sugar can cause weight gain because it is high in calories while providing few other nutrients. Added sugars are often referred to as "empty calories" since they are high in calories but low in nutrients such as vitamins, minerals, protein, fat, and fibre, which the body needs to function properly.
                    The World Health Organization <a href="https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789241549028">WHO(2015)</a>  recommends that "free" sugars make up no more than 10% of daily kilojoule intake to prevent unhealthy weight gain and dental caries.
